excerpt: 15th-century mansion attracting visitors for its unique Venetian Gothic architecture.
detail_description: Cipiko Palace, a 15th-century mansion in Trogir, Croatia, is renowned for its unique Venetian Gothic architecture. The palace was strategically positioned by the Cipiko family to occupy the western side of the main square, opposite significant public buildings. The southern portal features medallions of angels bearing Koriolan's motto 'Know thyself,' while the northern portal boasts intricate design work.
name: Cipiko Palace

excerpt: Small, fortified 15th-century castle offering picturesque city & harbor views.
detail_description: Kamerlengo Castle, located in Trogir, Croatia, is a small 15th-century fortress that offers stunning views of the city and harbor. Built by the republic of Venice, it began to deteriorate in the late 19th century but was later renewed after World War II. The castle is part of a rich tapestry of historical sites in Trogir, including the impressive Cathedral of St. Lawrence with its Romanesque entrance and the grand Cipiko Palace.
name: Kamerlengo Castle

excerpt: Trogir is a town on the central Adriatic coast of Croatia. Its preserved old town, known for its mix of Renaissance, baroque and Romanesque buildings, lies on a small island connected to the mainland and the island of Čiovo by bridges. The 13th-century Cathedral of St. Lawrence houses the Renaissance Chapel of St. John and offers sweeping views from its bell tower. Parts of the medieval city walls remain intact.
detail_description: Trogir, a town located on the central Adriatic coast of Croatia, boasts a well-preserved old town with a blend of Renaissance, baroque and Romanesque architecture. The old town is situated on a small island connected to the mainland and another island by bridges. Visitors can explore the 13th-century Cathedral of St. Lawrence which features the Renaissance Chapel of St. John and offers panoramic views from its bell tower.
name: Trogir

excerpt: Peaceful museum offering period furniture, famous portraits & exhibits on the city's unique history.
detail_description: Trogir City Museum, located in the Baroque Garagnin-Fanfogna Palace, offers a peaceful and insightful experience for history enthusiasts. The museum showcases period furniture, famous portraits, and exhibits detailing the city's unique history. Visitors can explore Greek and Roman artifacts, old manuscripts, drawings, paintings, as well as antique clothing and 18th-century furniture.
name: Trogir City Museum

detail_description: Trogir Old Town is a small medieval town located on an island off the Central Dalmatian coast of Croatia. It boasts impressive architectural landmarks such as St. Lawrence's Cathedral and the Garagnin-Fanfogna palace, which houses the Trogir Town Museum. The town offers a charming blend of cobblestone streets in the old quarter and beautiful beaches along the seaside promenades.
name: Trogir Old Town

detail_description: The Church and Monastery of St. Dominic, also known as St. Dominic Monastery, is a significant historical site in Trogir, Croatia. Established in 1265, the monastery features a church constructed between the 14th and 17th centuries. The interior showcases remarkable sculptures and ancient tombs of notable figures such as Ivan and Simon Sobota from the 15th century.
name: Church and monastery of St. Dominic

detail_description: City Loggia Trogir is a must-visit medieval complex where you can wander through unique shops and galleries, and even spot locations from the Game of Thrones series. The 14th-century Renaissance square features St. John and St. Lawrence reliefs, along with renowned works by Croatian sculptor Ivan Mestrovic. Nearby, the Venetian-Gothic-Renaissance Cipiko Palace once housed Trogir's nobles.
name: City Loggia Trogir
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II 7, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

excerpt: Popular for swimming & snorkeling, this 2-km long beach offers a lifeguard, showers & chair rentals.
detail_description: Okrug Gornji Beach, also known as Copacabana Beach, is a 2-km long stretch of pebbled shoreline located in the municipality of Okrug Gornji on Ciovo Island. It's a popular spot for swimming and snorkeling, with amenities such as lifeguards, showers, and chair rentals available. Accessible from Trogir Old Town via a bridge, the beach offers clear waters and opportunities for sunbathing and people-watching.
name: Okrug Gornji Beach

excerpt: Prominent 1200s cathedral with romanesque-gothic architecture & a bell tower visitors can climb.
detail_description: Saint Lawrence's Cathedral, located in Trogir, is a prominent 13th-century cathedral with a mix of Romanesque and Gothic architecture. The construction of the cathedral began in the 13th century and was completed in the 17th century, resulting in a blend of different architectural styles. One of its main highlights is the exterior portal created by Croatian sculptor Radovan, featuring intricate designs with exotic animals and fantastical creatures.
name: Cathedral of St. Lawrence
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: The Museum of Sacred Art, situated on the first floor of the Parish Court in Trogir, is a small yet captivating museum showcasing various religious manuscripts and paintings. Notable exhibits include a painting of St. John the Baptist from 1489 by Bellini and a striking almost life-size crucifix featuring the Triumphal Christ.
name: Museum of Sacred Art
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II 7, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: Clock Tower, located in Trogir, is a historic structure that offers panoramic views of the surrounding area. Adjacent to the town hall, this tower was built on the site of the church of St. Sebastian and features a sculpture of St. Sebastian. The tower is linked to a Loggia which likely served as a courtroom during Renaissance times and showcases artwork by Nikola Firentinac.
name: Clock Tower
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II 7, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: Tucked away in the winding streets of Trogir, the Church of St. Peter dates back to the 13th century and is thought to have been associated with a Benedictine monastery for women. Despite its unassuming exterior, this ancient church boasts striking Baroque-style architecture and is renowned for its sculpture of St. Peter, the apostle. While it may not immediately stand out among Croatia's many churches, a visit to appreciate its historical significance is well worth it.
name: Church of St. Peter

detail_description: The Church of St. Peter has a rich history as it was once associated with the Benedictine women's monastery, believed to have been established by the spouse of King Bela IV of Hungary.
name: Church of St. Peter

detail_description: The Church of St. Nicholas is home to a remarkable orange marble relief of Kairos, the Greek god of opportunity, dating back to the 3rd century. The Benedictine Monastery of St. Nicholas was established in 1064 by St. Ivana Trogir and has been continuously inhabited for almost a thousand years by nuns who have played significant roles in spirituality, Christian culture, and handicrafts within their city and beyond.
name: Church of St. Nicholas

detail_description: Trogir Promenade is a must-visit attraction in the historic center, featuring the impressive 15th-century Kamerlengo Fortress and Sveti Marko tower. The waterfront promenade, known as Riva, offers a charming setting with palm trees, spacious walkways, and numerous bars and restaurants. It provides stunning sunset views, opportunities for boat watching, and access to notable landmarks like Kamerlengo Castle and Marmonts Gloriette.
name: Trogir Promenade

detail_description: Trg Ivana Pavla II, also known as John Paul II Square in Croatian, is a prominent landmark that overlooks the charming surroundings of the town. The square offers stunning views of significant buildings such as the Town Hall, Clock Tower, and Town Loggia. It stands as a focal point in the area, attracting visitors with its impressive architecture and historical significance.
name: Trg Ivana Pavla II

detail_description: Green Market, located near the bridge to Trogir, offers a delightful experience of local life. Visitors can explore an array of fresh produce, flowers, honey, spices, wine and cheese. The market is conveniently situated in the center with easy access to restaurants, bus stations, supermarkets and more. It's a favorite spot for its scenic views by the water.
name: Green Market

detail_description: Nestled in the charming town of Trogir, Gelato Bar Bella is a must-visit for anyone with a penchant for delightful frozen treats. This beloved ice cream shop prides itself on using fresh, high-quality ingredients to create an array of both classic and innovative flavors. From the zesty Ricotta and Orange to the unique Lemon and Pistachio, there's something to tantalize every palate.
name: Gelato bar Bella
address: Ul. Blaža Jurjeva Trogiranina 5, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: Kula sv. Marka, also known as Trogir Tower of St. Mark, is an integral part of the city's fortifications, connected to the walls and featuring a cylindrical structure with semi-circular stepped menzola carrying bows former battlements. This small fort was built by the Venetians around 1430 to defend the strip of water separating the island from the mainland. While it is well-preserved and offers historic charm, visitors may find it closed on certain days.
name: Kula sv. Marka

detail_description: Knežev dvor, also known as the Town Hall, is a charming building located in the heart of Trogir. The inner courtyard is reminiscent of Juliets House in Verona and holds a special allure. While parts of the structure date back to the 15th century, it underwent extensive reconstruction at the end of the 19th century, incorporating remnants from the Duke's palace. Often overshadowed by other nearby attractions, this hidden gem is worth a visit.
name: Knežev dvor
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II 1, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: Park Garagnin-Fanfogna, located in Trogir, is a historic treasure housing the Trogir City Museum and an old library founded by Ivan Luka Garagnin. The palace has witnessed the presence of various civilizations over the centuries. Visitors can explore literary portraits from the mid-1700s and admire the late Baroque wing of the building.
name: Park Garagnin-Fanfogna

detail_description: The historic city of Trogir, a UNESCO World Heritage Monument since 1997, is a must-see destination near Split. Visitors often find it to be even more charming than expected, with its picturesque and serene atmosphere. It's described as a beautiful and perfect place to spend the day, making it an ideal stop for travelers exploring the region.
name: UNESCO World Heritage Monument

detail_description: The Blue Lagoon Tour (Route 3 Islands) is a must-visit destination in Croatia, offering stunning crystalline waters and fantastic snorkeling opportunities. Accessible via boat tour from Trogir, this excursion often includes visits to other nearby spots like Solta island and Solinska Bay. It's recommended to rent a 20hp boat for the day trip, which typically costs around 90-100 euros with a deposit of 50-100 euros.
name: BLUE LAGOON TOUR ( Route 3 Islands )

detail_description: Trogir is a stunning city with beautiful streets at every turn. The city boasts picturesque alleyways and charming architecture, making it a delightful place to explore.
name: Trogir

detail_description: Blue Lagoon by Max Nautica in Trogir offers a budget-friendly boat tour to the Blue Lagoon and other islands. The tour includes several hours at the Blue Lagoon, a simple lunch, and a visit to another island before returning to Trogir. Guests also receive watermelon on the return trip. Visitors praise the friendly staff and delicious food provided during the experience.
name: Blue Lagoon by Max Nautica - Trogir
address: Obala kralja Zvonimira bb, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: When visiting Trogir in Croatia, make sure to explore the Zbirka umjetnina Kairos, a small but exquisite collection of art. Housed in 3-4 rooms, this museum showcases beautiful pieces superbly presented for visitors to admire. Although the 5 entry fee may seem steep, it supports the monastery and is definitely worth it for art enthusiasts. While in Trogir, don't miss out on visiting the Cathedral of St. Nicholas and the place where St.
name: Zbirka umjetnina Kairos

detail_description: The Historic City of Trogir is a charming destination located on the Adriatic coast of Croatia. This well-preserved medieval town is renowned for its beautiful architecture, including stunning cathedrals, palaces, and towers. The city's rich history is evident in its narrow cobblestone streets and ancient buildings. Visitors can explore the impressive Kamerlengo Castle and St. Lawrence Cathedral, both UNESCO World Heritage sites.
name: Historic City of Trogir

detail_description: As you wander through the charming streets of Trogir, make sure to stop by the Sjeverna Gradska Vrata, a stunning 15th-century northern gate that serves as a grand entrance to the Old Town. This architectural gem showcases a blend of styles influenced by ancient Greeks, Romans, and Venetians. The gate features intricate details and is crowned with a Gothic statue of Trogir's patron saint, Blessed John of Trogir.
name: North Gate

detail_description: The Chapel of St. Sebastian, constructed in 1477 by Nicholas of Florence to protect the city from the plague, cleverly combines a church and a tower with a city clock in a small space. The facade features statues of St. Sebastian and Christ giving blessings. Visitors can climb the narrow spiral staircase to reach the top of the bell tower for panoramic views of the old town, which is over 2000 years old and under UNESCO's protection.
name: Chapel of St. Sebastian
address: Trg Ivana Pavla II 2, 21220, Trogir, Croatia

detail_description: Južna gradska vrata, also known as the Southern Town Gate, is a historic landmark in Trogir. Built in 1593, this massive gate has retained its original wooden sashes, offering a glimpse into the past. It serves as the southern entrance to the old town and opens onto the picturesque Riva waterfront.
name: South Gate

detail_description: Located in Central Dalmatia, Croatia, Čiovo and Trogir offer a blend of ancient history and modern vacation amenities. Trogir is a small medieval town with well-preserved architecture that reflects influences from Venice, Ancient Greece, and the Roman Empire. The city is surrounded by a wall and connected to the island of Čiovo by bridges. Visitors can enjoy various accommodation options including holiday homes, villas, resorts, recreational tourism facilities, and camping sites.
name: Čiovo - Trogir - Central Dalmatia Croatia - Bike Tracks

detail_description: Čiovo in Okrug Gornji, Central Dalmatia, Croatia offers a beautiful beach with clear water and various amenities like ice cream and corn vendors. Visitors recommend experiencing the amazingness of this place for themselves despite occasional crowding. The bridge to Čiovo from Trogir is closed, but a free ferry service is available nearby. In October, the weather is pleasant for swimming and enjoying the beach with fewer crowds.
name: Čiovo - Okrug Gornji - Central Dalmatia Croatia - Bike Tracks

detail_description: Atelier Uremovic is a charming art studio known for its excellent communication and beautiful artwork. Visitors praise the talented artist and describe the owner as a kind and pleasant individual. The studio is highly regarded for its exceptional service and impressive art, making it a must-visit destination for art enthusiasts.
name: Atelier Uremovic
